<ns2101:section xmlns:ns2101="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.grub.introduction.whatIsGrub">
    <ns2102:title xmlns:ns2102="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">What is GRUB?</ns2102:title>
    <ns2103:para xmlns:ns2103="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">GNU GRUB (GRand Unified Bootloader) is a Multiboot boot loader and is therefore
        responsible for loading and transferring control to an operating system kernel. (See <ns2104:xref xmlns:ns2104="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" linkend="resources.information.platforms.linux.kernel.introduction.whatIsKernel"/>) GRUB
        is both powerful and flexible by being able to load a variety of operating systems and by
        allowing you to specify how an operating system should be loaded. The kernel file name,
        drive and partition can be specified from a command line or a menu interface when booting
        with GRUB. Alternatively, a grub shell script can be executed from your operating system, to emulate and 
        install the boot loader. </ns2103:para>
    
    <ns2105:para xmlns:ns2105="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Before installing GRUB, take note that the device syntax has a different naming 
        convention in GRUB and needs to be noted when booting from a command line, e.g. 
        instead of <ns2106:literal xmlns:ns2106="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">hda</ns2106:literal>, this device is specified as <ns2107:literal xmlns:ns2107="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">(hd0,1)</ns2107:literal> 
        in GRUB where <ns2108:literal xmlns:ns2108="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">hd0</ns2108:literal> specifies the first hard drive and the 
        <ns2109:literal xmlns:ns2109="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">1</ns2109:literal> specifies the second partition. To access the disks or partitions 
        with GRUB, you need to use the device specification in a command, like 
        <ns2110:literal xmlns:ns2110="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">root (hd0)</ns2110:literal>. To specify a file you would type something like 
        <ns2111:literal xmlns:ns2111="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">(hd0)/vmlinuz</ns2111:literal> where <ns2112:literal xmlns:ns2112="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">vmlinuz</ns2112:literal> is the file name.</ns2105:para>
</ns2101:section>